{{no footnotes|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox cheese | name = Bondost | image = | othernames = | country = [[Sweden]] | region = | town = | source = Cows | pasteurised = | texture = Firm | fat = | protein = | dimensions = | weight = | aging = 6–8 weeks | certification = }}
'''Bondost''' (sometimes spelled '''bond-ost''', Swedish for "farmer cheese") is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] cheese, also made in the [[United States]], chiefly in [[New York (state)|New York]].
This [[cattle|cow]]'s-milk cheese is cylindrical in shape, about {{convert|13|cm|abbr=on}} across and {{convert|9|cm|abbr=on}} high. After the milk (either raw or [[pasteurization|pasteurized]]) is curdled, heated, cut, salted, stirred, pressed into forms, and immersed into brine for a day or two, the new cheese is ripened for six to eight weeks. Sometimes bondost is spiced with [[cumin]] or [[caraway seed]]s, which are incorporated into the curd just before it is molded.
It has a firm texture providing a mild tasting cheese that can be served as an appetizer or for snacking. When produced, it is brine cured, allowed to dry, and ready to serve in approximately 2 months. Several varieties are cured for 1 to 2 days, while the most flavorful varieties are cured for several weeks.
==See also== {{portal|Food}} * [[Brined cheese]] * [[List of cheeses]]
