{{unreferenced|date=October 2008}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}

There have been several '''military occupations of Luxembourg''' through the ages.  Amongst them have been:

* The French occupation of Luxembourg during the [[Franco-Spanish War (1635)|Franco-Spanish War]].  This led to the [[first Partition of Luxembourg]], with the loss of [[Thionville]], under the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]].
* The French occupation of Luxembourg before and during the [[War of the Grand Alliance]] (1684–1697).
* The [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] occupation of Luxembourg from 1815 until 1867.  Under the 1815 [[Treaty of Paris (1815)|Treaty of Paris]], which ended the [[Napoleonic Wars]], the fortress of [[Luxembourg City]] came under the control of the [[German Confederation]].  Thus, Luxembourg was occupied by Prussian soldiers until the 1867 [[Treaty of London, 1867|Treaty of London]] ordered an end to the occupation and the demolition of the fortifications.
* The [[German occupation of Luxembourg in World War I]] (1914–1918).
* The [[German occupation of Luxembourg in World War II]] (1940–1944).

[[Category:Military history of Luxembourg]]


